>> Defense-in-depth: deny URL smuggling into write-tool bodies.
>>
>> Sibling defense to no-novel-urls. Where no-novel-urls catches URL
>> *construction* attacks (agent base64-encodes a secret as a path on a
>> known-good domain), this guard catches URL *smuggling*: a URL that
>> exists verbatim somewhere in untrusted content gets carried into a
>> write body. Canonical attack — IT1: phishing URL injected into Bob's
>> slack message → summarized into Alice's DM body → recipient clicks.
>>
>> Implementation note (verified by zero-LLM probe):
>>   - Per-operation guard with `before op:exfil:send` plus a `for` over
>>     `@mx.args` was the cleanest design but mlld doesn't allow `for`
>>     expressions inline in guard `when` arms, and helper exes from the
>>     policy module don't resolve in the dispatch context (they'd need
>>     to be imported at every consumer site).
>>   - Per-input guards triggered by data labels (`before untrusted`,
>>     `before influenced`) work cleanly: they fire once per labeled
>>     input, see `@input` as the value (with full mx), and `@mx.op` for
>>     the operation context. Side-effect import registers them.
>>
>> So we declare two per-input guards (untrusted, influenced) that each
>> check whether the labeled input contains a URL and the current op is
>> exfil:send. If both, deny. The pair covers the smuggling vector
>> (untrusted source content + influenced LLM output that may carry it).
>>
>> Trigger note: bench uses `exfil:send` for all write-side exfil ops
>> (send_email, send_money, send_direct_message, schedule_meeting,
>> post_webpage). `exfil:fetch` is read-side and not a smuggling target.
>>
>> Conservative trade-off: without per-URL provenance tracking, if a
>> body string concatenates user-task text and untrusted content, the
>> whole arg's taint propagates untrusted, so even URLs that originated
>> in user task get denied. This is the safe choice in v1.
>> policy.urls.allowConstruction remains as the operator-level escape
>> hatch.
>>
>> See c-84d5 (this guard's ticket), c-1d65 (summarize_url primitive
>> that pairs with this guard for safe summarize-and-send patterns).

guard @noUntrustedUrlsInOutput before untrusted = when [
  @input.mx.urls.length > 0 && @mx.op.labels.includes("exfil:send")
    => deny "URL in untrusted-source input cannot flow to a write-tool body. Route the URL through a fact-bearing record field or use the summarize_url primitive (c-1d65)."
  * => allow
]

>> NOTE: a parallel `before influenced` guard would catch URLs in
>> LLM-output that crossed an untrusted-content boundary. Initial test
>> showed the influenced trigger interfered with extract-worker tests
>> (scalar-extract-payload + coerce-extract-rejects-degenerate-output
>> regressed). Defer the influenced variant pending investigation; the
>> untrusted variant covers the IT1 phishing-smuggling case (URL in
>> source content reaches body before LLM influence is applied).
